			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">WHY!?~<a name="50700"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jul 8 04 12:15 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Ok. I just spent some time reading what other bards are posting to the 'official' threads on the station boards and I just want to scream, rant, and throw things! 
<br />

<br />
I love and adore my bard. Why? Mostly because it is hands down the most versatile class in EQ.
<br />

<br />
So... Why the h*ll are BARDS crying and whining for something that does nothing for gameplay except make bardbots more viable and actual PLAYED bards less versatile to the point that bard-bots are clearly superior? Yes, I'm referring to all the auto-twist suggestions. Want to be a caster or melee? give up your bard. STOP trying to make bards into singing rangers! 
<br />

<br />
Think about it please. Why would ANY raiding guild want an actual PLAYED bard when they can easily have 2-boxed bardbots for AE resists, AE mana, MT songs, etc that won't earn RPP, won't roll against other plate classes (esp. warriors &amp; clerics), and won't try to get the guild to target bard-gear mobs? Unless the guild uses bards extensively for pulling, which has become a secondary role for bards to fill and diminished lately, a bardbot will indeed fulfill all/most of a bard's utility on a raid.
<br />

<br />
Someone please, please explain to me why this is desirable? 
<br />

<br />
Twisting is the single gameplay dynamic that limits a bard. It is the one single response to every shout of &quot;overpowered&quot; that we all hear. It is also one of the true measures of a bard. If a bard comes to you and tells you they've macroed their twist to a single hotkey how do you respond? With incredulity and disdain? Probably, because they have limited their abilities as a bard by creating that hotkey and shown that they have no true idea what a bard is capable of. 
<br />

<br />
So... Again... Why are bards crying to have done to them what we all disdain in bards now?</span></td>
