				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: WHY!?~<a name="53718"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jul 26 04 2:59 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span><blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">If you can have MULTIPLE effects up almost indefinitely from pushing 1 button the &quot;balance&quot; to songs NOT costing mana is completely lost.</span></blockquote>
<br />
Do you really find that twisting is so crippling in your game-play?  What I'm saying is, it's not like I can't twist multiple songs and keep them up indefinitely.  Honestly, I could start when I wake up in the morning, and keep 3 songs in my song box all day until I go to bed.  So why should I have to manually do it <b>just to be reasonably effective?</b>  Listen, if bard songs were meant to be individually powerful, twisting would be considered an exploit.  As it stands, the bard class is centered on the notion of having multiple effects happening at the same time, hence why the songs have small effects and they are all different so as to work together.
<br />

<br />
Gonna talk about that part I highlighted a second.  Think about the work you do during your playtime.  You are pushing 1-2 keys (depending on whether you macro or not) every 3 seconds, regardless of how effective the songs actually are, and independent of all other factors (except mez and pulling).  Now let's look at a cleric.  Depending on how hard the mobs hit, and how good of a tank they are backing up, a cleric might not have to cast a single spell during a whole fight.  Which means that they are free to heal at their leisure, because they are not dependent on timing.  And a CH cast is 10 seconds long, 1 key press.  During the same time, a bard would be hitting 3-6 keys, and the effectiveness of his songs would be greatly overshadowed by comparison.  My 80hp per tick regen will not keep a tank alive, but an 8k complete heal will.
<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">Consider it the &quot;cost&quot; of being able to do all that you CAN do. </span></blockquote>
<br />
Let's see what I *can* do, shall we?
<br />
The other day I did an ikkinz trial, singular might.  Just killed the Pixtt Annihilator.  The parse numbers were something like: Me - 75dps, Ranger - 200dps, Warrior - 165dps(!!), Enchanter - 110dps, and the cleric and druid were chain healing so no dps from them.  All I did during the fight was &quot;all I can do&quot;, I played chorus of marr, echo of the trusik, war march of the mastruq, and psalm of veeshan.  Even if you take all the indirect dps added by me from echo of the trusik, and factor in the 85pt damage shield, still I would come up at about 190dps.  Why would they pick me over a rogue in this situation?  Rogue is more dps, and honestly better utility in these trials...the only thing I added was the security of having the bard songs in the window.  And even the mana regen is negligible.  The fight lasted 2 minutes, which means the cleric cast HL about 18 times, and during those 2 minutes he would have recovered roughly 500 mana from chorus of marr, which isn't even enough to cast holy light 1 time.  So again, twisting is making me have to bust my nuts off just to get by, or earn my keep if you will, whereas a rogue could have been cruising through the fight just hitting backstab or probably using a macro to do that for him.
<br />

<br />
Now let's discuss the effect that manual twisting has on the average bard.  How many people make bards because they want to be the &quot;life of the party&quot; class?  Come on, raise your hands, you know you did.  Unless I map my hotkeys to f-keys or numpad keys, or if I use alt+# to twist, I can't type a complete sentence the whole time I'm in a group.  Again using a cleric as an example...they could have a whole conversation during a fight, and be able to think out clearly what they're doing without feeling retarded like I do when I type in 2 second bursts.  So I'm left to lose people from my friend's list and also be unable to communicate clearly during a group unless I stop everything I'm doing.  This is a handicap I shouldn't have to have.
<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">Twisting has been a fact of life for a bard since day one. It part of the class. In fact, its a defining charactistic of the class. Changing it damages the integrity of the class.</span></blockquote>
<br />
I guess I just have to ask a question at the end of all this.  What is it about manual twisting that defines a bard?  I had the hang of twisting 3-4 songs at a time before I hit level 10.  I could pretty much twist in my sleep at this point, what's wrong with wanting a functional program client-side or even server-side to do it for me?  As long as it worked like 1 song at a time like how I normally play, just kept them going in rotation so I don't have to mess with it.
<br />

<br />
Lazy nothing.  Make the game enjoyable for me so I can look up from my goddamn spell casting bar once in awhile, please.  I don't even know what half the mobs we raid look like because I have my head buried in text making sure everything is going as planned.
<br />

<br />
These posts are getting really long and I apologize, but this is a major issue in my opinion.  Twisting is a hindrance to the fun level I have when I play the game.</span></td>
