				<td colspan="2"><span>Gotta add just a little more to my previous post.
<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">you want to use your voice or insturments to fill peoples arms with strength or speed, to heal their wounds, or to confuse a mob, you have to keep singing.</span></blockquote>
<br />
This logic confuses me.  That's like the same as saying a healer should have to upkeep their heal in order for it not to fade, or to upkeep their enchantment.  When a cleric calls the strength of the gods upon his warrior companion, wouldn't he have to enter a meditative state to keep the blessing upon him?  Leave roleplaying at the door please, this game is far beyond where it started out, and honest to god roleplaying just isn't a factor anymore.
<br />

<br />
And then this one
<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">Consider Alt+ 11,22,33,44,55,11,22,33,44,55...... akin to playing your insturments while you weave 5 songs together into a cresendo of inspiring power.</span></blockquote>
<br />
You make it sound as if my songs are of epic proportions.  Please.  If you are roleplaying, sure.  If you're playing the game, no.  The twist I mentioned in my above post is pretty much the only songs worth playing at level 65.  And the effect of them is very marginal, other than probably the echo of trusik, or chorus of marr over extended periods of time.  But yet if I don't keep at least 3 of the 4 up (I always drop psalm unless there's something to resist), I get labelled a bad player, just because I don't feel like mashing 3 keys over and over again till the day's end.
<br />

<br />
Come on!  My boots have a percussion mod, what, like I stomp out a rhythm?  Ok, I'll give you that, now wrap your head around this: My arms have a stringed mod.  Yeah, because I have guitars for armplates obviously.  It doesn't make any sense, it's just a game.  And playing the game shouldn't require me to work 3x as hard as another player just to get my little job done.
<br />

<br />
The only argument against an auto-twist is just the fear of change.  Think of it like this.  I have to work my butt off to keep 3 songs up (well not work my butt off but at least pay attention and watch my timing), what if warriors had to work their butts off to keep swinging at a mob?  Warriors don't even have to participate in a fight beyond hitting autoattack.  On a permarooted mob, a warrior could turn on autoattack and go fix himself something to eat.  Why can't I do the same?  Would you claim warriors are overpowered in that respect because their job is being done for them by the client?  How is it different for bards and twisting?</span></td>
